<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06151112 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06151112 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  STOCK; CLOSING; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Stock prices jumped ahead today, carrying the Dow Jones industrial averageback above the 3,000 mark.;    The Dow average of 30 blue chips was up 30.86points at 3,000.45.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DOW AVERAGE JUMPS PAST 3,000 AGAIN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Chart attached at end of article  </MEMO><TEXT>     The index was up 69.55 points over the past three sessions.;    The markethas come back to life of late as hopes have built up that the economy willsoon mount a sustained recovery from the recession.;    Fresh support for thatoptimism is expected Friday when the government reports on the Index ofLeading Economic Indicators for April.;    By analysts' estimates, the index,which is designed to detect future economic trends, will show a gain in therange of 0.2 percent to 0.5 percent. That would mark its third consecutivemonthly increase.;    But some observers still worry that any recovery in suchthings as corporate profits is likely to be slow and fitful, carrying the riskof unpredictable disappointments.;    In other economic news, the governmentsaid today that consumer spending, which would be the muscle behind anyeconomic recovery, fell 0.1 percent in April.;    At the same time, theCommerce Department reported that personal incomes edged up 0.1 percent.;   Consumers are expected to lead the economy out of recession, since theirspending represents two-thirds of the nation's economic activity.;    But someanalysts have expressed concern over recent surveys that have shown an erosionin consumer confidence that had surged following the gulf war.;    &quot;Thisturnaround apparently represents the shift in public focus from February'sdazzling military victory in the Persian Gulf to the grim reality of recessionon the home front,&quot; economists at Fuji Securities in Chicago wrote in theirweekly newsletter.;    Meanwhile, Commerce and the Department of Housing andUrban Development said in a second report that sales of new homes rose 1.2percent in April, their third increase in a row. That bolstered analysts'contentions that the housing recession, at least, hit bottom in January.;   The two departments said that sales of single-family homes totaled aseasonally adjusted annual rate of 500,000 units, up from 494,000 in March.;   In another report, the government said today that the number of Americansfiling new claims for unemployment benefits fell slightly again in mid-May.;   The Labor Department said that for the week ended May 18, the number ofpeople filing first-time unemployment claims fell by 9,000, down to 445,000from the previous week's mark of 454,000.;    The decline followed a5,000-drop in the previous week.; THE MARKETS; In trading    today:; ...; TheDow average rose 30.86 points to 3,000.45.; ...; July crude oil added 14 centsto $21.25  a barrel.; ...; In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.08 yen to a closing137.68 yen.; ...; In Zurich, gold was $360.85 an ounce, down 15 cents.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910530  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  463  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday May 30, 199100151112,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>